title: Roundup (Oct. 20): Glenelg Country girls soccer completes perfect regular season
text:
var ssaUrl = ('https:' == document.location.protocol ? 'https://' : 'http://') + 'pixel.sitescout.com/iap/0ea84626951144d2';new Image().src = ssaUrl;"/> Sports Roundup (Oct. 20): Glenelg Country girls soccer completes perfect regular season Haley Toomer Nicole Munchel / Baltimore Sun Media Group 
Glenelg Country's Haley Toomer kicks the ball up the field. 
Glenelg Country's Haley Toomer kicks the ball up the field. (Nicole Munchel / Baltimore Sun Media Group) Baltimore Sun Staff Report 
The Glenelg Country School girls soccer team shut out Park, 3-0, on Tuesday to allow the Dragons to complete a perfect regular season. 
They finish with an 11-0, 9-0 record in the Interscholastic Athletic Association of Maryland C Conference. 
Addie Schmidt had a goal and an assist against the visiting Bruins (8-5, 6-3). 
No. 12 Atholton 2, Long Reach 0: Holly Edsoll scored twice to lead the host Raiders (11-2) past the Lightning (3-6-2). 
No. 13 Perry Hall 3, Dulaney 0: Rachel Bohli had two goals and an assist to lift the Gators (9-4) over the host Lions (7-3). 
Boys soccer 
Harford Tech 2, Elkton 1, 2OT: Micah Barton scored the game-winner on an assist from Mark Maust in the 91st minute as the host Cobras (6-5) beat the Golden Elks (2-7-2). 
Harford Tech's Brian Triolo forced overtime with a goal at the 46th minute. 
No. 3 Perry Hall 4, Dulaney 0: Gaige Robinson had three assists as the host Gators (12-2) beat the Lions (2-10-1) 
No. 11 Meade 1, Southern 0, OT: Paul Kayson scored the game-winner in the 85th minute to lift the visiting Mustangs (12-1) over the Bulldogs (2-8-1). 
No. 12 Bel Air 2, Patterson Mill 1: The host Bobcats (9-1-3) scored the game-winner in the second half to edge the Huskies (9-5). 
No. 15 North Harford 6, Rising Sun 2: Khaled Abuhantash had a hat trick, and the host Hawks (8-1-2) jumped out to a 5-0 lead at the half. 
The Tigers fell to 3-6. 
Severna Park 1, Broadneck 0: August Pasquale scored in the first half to lead the Falcons (8-3-2) over the host Bruins (6-3-1). 
Field hockey 
No. 1 Archbishop Spalding 4, Severn 1: Erin Shanahan scored twice to lead the host Cavaliers (13-0-1) past the Admirals (7-7). 
Severn's defense turned away 14 penalty corners. 
No. 2 Garrison Forest 2, Notre Dame Prep 1 : The host Grizzlies (14-1-1) took a 2-0 lead at the half and held off the Blazers (5-5). 
Sam Fiedler and Hailey Mules scored for Garrison Forest. 
No. 6 Marriotts Ridge 6, River Hill 0: Allie McAuley had three assists and the host Mustangs (12-1) shut out the Hawks (9-4). 
No. 15 Mount Hebron 8, Wilde Lake 0: Katie Anderson put together back-to-back hat tricks in wins over the host Wildecats (2-12) and against visiting Fallston, 3-2 in overtime on Monday. 
The Vikings improved to 11-3. 
Girls volleyball 
No. 5 River Hill d. Marriotts Ridge, 3-1: The host Hawks (9-1, 9-1) continued their pursuit of the county title. River Hill played an emphatic second-set win, which was followed up with two tight set victories to beat the visiting Mustangs (6-5, 5-5), 15-25, 25-7, 25-22, 25-22, on its Dig Pink night. 
"They just has to refocus and play the ball they know how to play," coach Lynn Paynter said. "Marriotts Ridge is a relentless team – you see how many matches they have gone to five sets. ... We knew we had to be prepared for defending a lot of balls." 
—Tim Schwartz, 
Baltimore Sun Media Group 
Golf 
Harford County championship: Bel Air senior Spencer Comitz and Aberdeen junior Mitchell Hardin won individual Harford County championships at Geneva Farm Golf Course. 
Comitz shot 82 to win her second straight county crown by 12 strokes, while Hardin fired a three-over par 75 to win by a stroke over runner-up Ryan Shuck of Harford Tech, who shot 76. Fallston's Dylan Wolf was third with 77. 
Wolf's finish led Fallston to the team title with an eight-player score of 504. C. Milton Wright was second with 516 and Tech, third with 523. 
—Randall L. McRoberts, 
Baltimore Sun Media Group 
Water polo 
Loyola Blakefield 14, Calvert Hall 13, OT: The host Dons (9-7) scored twice in the closing two minutes of overtime to beat the Cardinals (14-5). 
Ben Brown and Sammy Logue had five goals each, and Brandon Elliott made 16 saves for Loyola. 
Baltimore Sun staff contributed to this article.
